  "body": "## Issue\r\n\r\nTruffle v5's compiler auto-downloading works for solcjs but not for Docker. It's likely that we want to avoid requiring the user to grab the image themselves.\r\n\r\nEffectively, when the user does not have the Docker image, Truffle should run `docker pull ethereum/solc:<image-version>`.\r\n\r\nTruffle should select the best-match `image-version` for the user's specified config value, similar to how the code works for solcjs. (_see implementation: [`CompilerSupplier.prototype.getCached(version)`](https://github.com/trufflesuite/truffle/blob/next/packages/truffle-compile/compilerSupplier.js#L128-L155)_)\r\n\r\nWe probably **do not** want to run `docker pull` in the situation where we already have the image, since that adds seemingly-unnecessary overhead.\r\n\r\nIt is possible that there are reasons why we don't want to do this, either for user-experience or because there are technical limitations that make it harder to implement. I remember @cgewecke mentioning this when he was writing CompilerSupplier initially, but I don't remember his reasoning. Any implementation of this capability should probably keep this in mind and consider UX first.\r\n\r\n## Actual Results\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ truffle compile\r\nError: Please pull 0.4.22 from docker before trying to compile with it.\r\n at CompilerSupplier.errors (compilerSupplier.js:518:10)\r\n at CompilerSupplier.validateDocker (compilerSupplier.js:362:16)\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Environment\r\n\r\n* Truffle version (`truffle version`): `v5.0.0-next.15`-ish\r\n",
